    "userId": 576873518, 
    "messageBody": "<div id=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><html><head></head>David,<div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">That is certainly true, but you could say the same for many of the assert functions. For example, instead of assertNull one could use assertTrue(x == null) or assertEquals(x, null). The assertNull function looks nicer, of course, but it can be done. In the same vein, an assertEmpty, while not necessary functionally, would provide the benefit of cleaner looking code, in my opinion.</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Best,</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Mark</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div><blockquote><span title=\"qreply\"> <blockquote type=\"cite\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">On Oct 4, 2015, at 10:14 PM, David Saff <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:saff@...\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">saff@...</a> [junit] &lt;<a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">junit@yahoogroups.com</a>&gt; wrote:</div><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734Apple-interchange-newline\"><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734ygrp-mlmsg\" style=\"font-size:13px;font-family:Arial, helvetica, clean, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;background-color:rgb(255, 255, 255);\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734ygrp-msg\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734ygrp-text\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;font-family:Georgia;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734webkit-block-placeholder\"></div><div dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Mark,<div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Thanks for your mail.&nbsp; Your idea sounds intriguing.&nbsp; However, it seems that assertEquals(Optional.none(), x) or assertEquals(Optional.of(y), x) would provide most of the benefit, wouldn&#39;t they?</div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">&nbsp; &nbsp;David</div></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734gmail_extra\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734gmail_quote\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\">On Sun, Oct 4, 2015 at 1:55 PM, Mark Silvis<span class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:masilvis22@...\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">masilvis22@...</a><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>[junit]<span class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span><span dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">&lt;<a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">junit@yahoogroups.com</a>&gt;</span><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>wrote:<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><blockquote class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734gmail_quote\" style=\"margin:0px 0px 0px 4px;line-height:1.22em;border-left-width:1px;border-left-color:rgb(204, 204, 204);border-left-style:solid;\"><u style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></u><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;background-color:rgb(255, 255, 255);\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><span style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">&nbsp;</span><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><p style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">I would like to contribute to JUnit, and I think I have a good idea for a feature. I’ve found that it would be nice to have assertions that explicitly supported Java 8’s Optional class. I’m thinking something along the lines of assertEmpty() and assertPresent(). Would such an addition be welcomed?<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Thanks,<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\">Mark<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></p></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;color:rgb(255, 255, 255);min-height:0px;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div></div></div></div></blockquote></div><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734webkit-block-placeholder\"></div></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;color:rgb(255, 255, 255);height:0px;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div></div></div></div></blockquote></span></blockquote></div><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-1750239734\"></div></html></div>", 
